<PageLayout
	title="About Nikhil Kashyap"
	description="Self-taught builder, founder, and AI x Hardware enthusiast."
>
	<section class="content-shell py-12 space-y-8"> 
		<div class="space-y-3 max-w-3xl">
			<p class="m-0 text-ink text-2xl font-semibold leading-tight">I'm a 21-year-old self-taught builder from Bareilly. I left school after 10th grade to learn by building — and have been doing exactly that for the last five years.</p>
			
			<p class="m-0 text-muted">It started in 9th grade with a Facebook page called Micro Electronics. By the time I was 17, it had 20,000+ followers and brands like JLCPCB, NextPCB, Tuya, LCSC, and Drona Aviation were paying me for partnerships. I used the money — and the free 3D printers, drones, and dev kits — to build a full hardware lab in my bedroom. Then I turned the brand into a product company, designed and sold STEM kits, and ran robotics workshops for kids at Gujarat Science City with WitBlox.</p>
			
			<p class="m-0 text-muted">My first real venture was NeuraliX — an attempt to make brain-computer interface hardware affordable for hobbyists. I designed Neuronify, an open-source biosignal development board that records EEG, EMG, ECG, and EOG signals on a single device. It didn't reach commercial scale, but it taught me how to ship original hardware and produced work on EOG-based eye-blink detection and early ADHD detection using ML.</p>
			
			<p class="m-0 text-muted">Then I joined Cretile in Bangalore as a Hardware Design Engineer — designing PCBs, writing firmware, building robotic prototypes, and shipping a custom IoT kit for an external client. I also built two internal AI tools applying LLMs to ERP and CRM workflows.</p>
			
			<p class="m-0 text-muted">Along the way, I've been backed by Emergent Ventures (Mercatus Center), the Inflection Grant (Long Journey Ventures), and Sigma91.</p>
			
			<p class="m-0 text-muted">Today I'm the founder and CEO of AlterAI, where I'm building Maya — an AI companion designed to remember you, understand you over time, and be honest with you instead of just agreeable. Maya comes with Halo, a hardware companion that gives it a real presence on your desk.</p>
			
			<p class="m-0 text-muted">My pattern is consistent: teach myself a domain by building inside it, ship real artifacts, and treat every project as a paid education in a new discipline.</p>
		</div>
	</section>
</PageLayout>
